## Two Installation Options

You can install the <%= vars.product_full %> environment in two ways:

1. Using `install-lab.sh` script:
    The `install-lab.sh` script automates the installation steps. Using this option you will only be required
    to download files and provide private registry endpoint, username and password.
1. Install manually:
    This option will require more interactivity from you, but you can have a more comprehensive understanding of
    what is happening.

## Installing Using Install-lab.sh Script

<p class="note">
If you want to install manually instead of using the install-lab.sh script,
skip to <a href="#install-manually">Installing Manually</a> section
</p>

1. This approach requires a image private registry that will be used to upload the docker installation images, 
so start by verifying and taking not of your private registry endpoint, username and password.

1. Get <%= vars.product_full %> Resources From <%= vars.product_network %>:

    * Log in and navigate to **<%= vars.product_full %>** in
       [<%= vars.product_network %>](https://network.pivotal.io/products/container-services-manager)
       and download the following resources:
   
       + **The <%= vars.product_full %> Command Line Interface (CLI):** Click **CLIs** and download
       the CLI for your operating system.
       + **<%= vars.product_full %> Helm chart TGZ file:** Click **Helm Chart for <%= vars.product_full %>** and
       download the Helm chart TGZ file.
       + **Images**: Click **Images** and download the daemon, broker, minio and chartmuseum Docker images
       + **install-lab.sh script**: Click **<%= vars.product_full %> Lab Environment Installer** and download the install-lab.sh file
       
1. Make the install-lab.sh file executable by executing the `chmod +x install-lab.sh` command
1. You need to provide the registry endpoint, username and password during the installation. To do that you can either:
  
  + execute the `./install-lab.sh` command and answer the registry details questions, or
  + create a registry.yaml file containing the needed information in the following format, and execute the `install-lab.sh registry.yaml` command

    #### registry.yaml template
    ```yaml
    registry: <my-registry-endpoint>/<project>/<repository>
    username: <username>
    password: <password>
    ```
    
1. Use the command `kubectl get services -n sm` to monitor the provisioning of the External IPs for daemon and broker services
1. Once the External IP is available for the daemon, you can configure the <%= vars.product_full %> environment variables by running the
  `source ./setSmEnv.sh` command
1. Once the External IP is available for the broker, you can configure <%= vars.product_full %> for cf by running the following script: 
  
    ```bash
    ./setCfDetails.sh <broker-name> <cf-api-endpoint> <cf-api-client> <cf-api-client-secret>
     where:
        <broker-name>     - is a name you will provide to your broker to be identified in cf
        <cf-api-endpoint> - is the cf endpoint. You can verify that by executing the "cf target" command
        <cf-api-endpoint> - is the cf client
        <cf-api-endpoint> - is the cf client secret
    ```
   
1. Test the <%= vars.product_full %> by calling `<%= vars.product_short %> version` or `<%= vars.product_short %> offer list` commands
1. You're done here! Jump to [Next Steps](#next-steps)

